A data product is a kind of packaging of a data set that can then be consumed by users, other data products or systems. A data product can combine data from different data sources and process the data.
A data product is described by a data product specification.

A data source is, for example, an operational system or an external database that our data products can retrieve data from. It is described by a data source specification. In many ways, a data source is like a data product, but with the difference that we are only interested in the data source's output and that we cannot influence how the data source is implemented.

Traits are used to annotate certain objects with additional metadata.
It could for instance be that a specific column contains an email-adress or that the entire dataset can be used for research.

Within the European Health Data Space, the secondary use of health data (for research, policy making, innovation...) will be enhanced, with the aim to make health data and health information more Findable, Accessible, Interoperable and Reusable. Researchers, for instance, will have access to larger amounts of high-quality, representative data, in a more efficient and less expensive way, through data access bodies in the EU countries, that guarantee the privacy of the patients.
In order to support the interoperability of health data (for secondary use) in the EHDS, a new standard has been developed: HealthDCAT-AP. It aims to establish standardised description of datasets for all health catalogues. Such metadata standard will improve the interoperability and findability of datasets for data users, across the "HealthData@EU" infrastructure, comprising Health Data Access Bodies in European countries, relevant authorised participants, and the EU Datasets Catalogue.
HealthDCAT-AP standard will also support health data holders in fullfilling the requirements of the new EHDS Regulation (see article 41.2).
DIML will implement support for HealthDCAT-AP

The Observational Medical Outcomes Partnership (OMOP) Common Data Model (CDM) is an open community data standard, designed to standardize the structure and content of observational data and to enable efficient analyses that can produce reliable evidence. A central component of the OMOP CDM is the OHDSI standardized vocabularies. The OHDSI vocabularies allow organization and standardization of medical terms to be used across the various clinical domains of the OMOP common data model and enable standardized analytics that leverage the knowledge base when constructing exposure and outcome phenotypes and other features within characterization, population-level effect estimation, and patient-level prediction studies.
DIML will implement support for OMOP

DimlDataBuilder is a Command Line Tool (CLI) that is used to read a DataProductSpecification and, based on its contents, generate the necessary artifacts to create the DataProduct in a given target platform. These artifacts can be everything from Infrastructure as Code scripts to SQL scripts and data pipeline instructions.
Download DimlDataBuilder from releases and extract it to a folder in your file system. Open your terminal and navigate to the executable. Now you can start using DimlDataBuilder.
Generates artifacts for a given target platform based on a DataProductSpecification.
--data-product (Required)
A file path or DIML ID to a DataProductSpecification.
--output-dir (Required)
A file path to an output directory where the resulting artifacts will be written.
--local-override (Optional)
A folder path to use as a local override for DIML ID:s. The folder path will replace the host of a DIML ID (i.e https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Region-Skane-SDI/diml-samples/main/sample_dataproduct.dataproduct --> C:/src/LocalOverridePath/Region-Skane-SDI/diml-samples/main/sample_dataproduct.dataproduct). This is useful when you need to work with local DIML specifications, since you won't need to change DIML ID for your specification and all of its dependencies.
--config (Optional)
A DIML ID to a DimlConfig specification.
--override (Optional)
Overrides previously created SQL scripts. This means that it adds DROP/REPLACE statements before the create statements.
--verbose (Optional)
Activates verbose logging to the console.
-v, --version (Optional)
Prints out version information.
-h, --help (Optional)
Prints out help information.
Generate artifacts based on a DataProductSpecification in GitHub

Pseudonymiseringsproxy för Dataplattformen. Designad för att placeras mellan Azure Data Factory (eller liknande) och själva datakällan vid ingest.
I dagsläget stöds enbart Microsoft SQL Server som datakälla.
En hämtning ses som en session, i varje session hämtas datan genom ett antal batcher. Storleken på varje batch anges i den request som påbörjar sessionen.
Pseudonymiseringen går på vilka kolumner som finns med i tabellen i dataproduktspecifikationen för att avgöra vilka kolumner som ska hämtas från källan. Kolumner som är markerade med traiten PII kommer att krypteras. Har kolumnen datatypen SSN (dvs personnummer) så kommer den först att normaliseras och sen krypteras då alla kolumner med datatypen SSN automatiskt har traiten PII.
För att starta en ny session skickas en request om detta till /mssql/start
För att sen hämta nästa batch anropas den URL som kommer med tillbaka i batchsvaret, den ligger på /mssql/batch/{sessionId}

The purpose of the validate datastage is to automate certain common checks and controls, and define how to handle data rows depending on the outcome of these operations. The validation can be applied to a dataproduct as a whole, and/or for specific tables.
Currently two policies can be defined:
flag: This will add a column which partitions on the unique key and counts the rows in these partitions. If more then one row is found in a partition, the column value is set to 0, otherwise to 1.
eliminate: This will add column for the row number within the partition created above.
flag: This will add a column where the value is set to 0 if the unique key is NULL, otherwise to 1.
setDefaultValue: This will set a default value for the unique key if it is NULL.
In addition to this, an action can be defined to control the behaviour of the data product:
ignoreValid: validation errors are ignored, so rows with key NULL values or duplicates will travel to the next stage.
stop: if a validation error is detected, the validation program will cast an error. No filter is applied to the output view though.
eliminateOnly: if a validation error is detected, the validation program will cast an error, and invalid rows will be filtered in the output view.
filterValid: invalid rows will be filtered in the output view.
The policies and related actions can be found here: https://github.com/Region-Skane-SDI/diml/tree/0a7f7acc6c8636b59c6a44b8e7cbd8dd3c6f1fd2/src/Diml.Library/Data/ValidationPolicies
